'''IBM Laboratory Vienna''' was an [[IBM]] research laboratory based in [[Vienna]], [[Austria]].
The laboratory started with a group led by [[Heinz Zemanek]] that moved from the [[Technische Hochschule]] (now the [[Technical University of Vienna]]).<ref name="jones90">{{cite book| first=Cliff B. | last=Jones | authorlink=Cliff Jones (computer scientist) | title=Systematic software development using VDM | publisher=[[Prentice-Hall]] | year=1990 | page=1 }}</ref> Initially, the group worked on [[computer hardware]] projects. Later a [[compiler]] for the [[ALGOL 60]] programming language was produced. The group built on ideas of [[Calvin Elgot|Calvin C. Elgot]], [[Peter Landin]], and [[John McCarthy (computer scientist)|John McCarthy]], to create an [[operational semantics]] that could define the whole of IBM's [[PL/I]] programming language. The [[meta-language]] used for this was dubbed by people outside the laboratory as the [[Vienna Definition Language]] (VDL). These descriptions were used for [[compiler design]] research into compiler design during 1968–70.<ref name="jl71">{{cite article| | first1=Cliff B. | last1=Jones | first2=Peter | last2=Lucas | authorlink2=Peter Lucas (computer scientist) | title=Proving correctness of implementation techniques | editor-first1=E. | editor-last1=Engeler | work=A Symposium on Algorithmic Languages | volume=188 | series=[[Lecture Notes in Mathematics]] | pages=178–211 | publisher=[[Springer-Verlag]] | year=1971 }}</ref>
The [[formal method]] VDM ([[Vienna Development Method]]) was a result of research at the laboratory by [[Dines Bjørner]], [[Cliff Jones (computer scientist)|Cliff Jones]], [[Peter Lucas (computer scientist)|Peter Lucas]], and others.<ref name="jones90" />
